I would prefer regex-based tokenizing from C++11 over C functions `strtok` or `strtok_s`:

    void split(const std::string&amp; s)
    {
       std::regex rgx(&quot;[~`!@#$%^&amp;*()-_+=,./?;:&#39;]+&quot;);
       std::sregex_token_iterator iter(s.begin(), s.end(), rgx, -1);
       std::sregex_token_iterator end;
       for ( ; iter != end; ++iter)
          std::cout &lt;&lt; *iter &lt;&lt; std::endl;
    }

IMO, it&#39;s much better since it works with `std::string` insted of char arrays (C strings).

A simple use case:

    std::string s(&quot;some`string?to+-be;:&#39;tokenized&quot;);
    split(s);

[Live demo here](https://wandbox.org/permlink/Cw7qRd3rBldShLsh).

---

Note that this will create `std::string` objects for sub-matches, which may represent some overhead (though possibly reduced by short string optimization). This question discusses how to turn sub-matches into `std::string_view` objects: [Iterating regex submatches represented as std::basic_string_view
](https://stackoverflow.com/q/50676058/580083).

